  "mission":[
    "The Department of Innovation and Technology is the City&rsquo;s enterprise wide technology services organization providing solutions that enable our business partners across all City departments. DoIT&rsquo;s primary day-to-day responsibility is to ensure that the networks, desktop computers, e-mail systems, and applications that support the business of City government are continuously available and operating effectively. DoIT embraces its responsibility to help manage costs through difficult financial times by continuously improving the cost structure of the City&rsquo;s technology without compromising service. Our commitment to being environmentally responsible is often synergistic with these economic and service responsibilities."
  ],
  "description_of_services":[
    "The Department of Innovation and Technology (DoIT) improves the delivery of government services to the public through the effective management of the City&rsquo;s existing and emerging technologies. DoIT introduces innovative technologies and processes designed to drive efficiency into government operations. DoIT also provides professional project management and business analysis services, in addition to maintaining the hardware and software platforms necessary to support the daily technical and communication operations of the City. Personnel skilled in programming, analysis, hardware and software support, training, communications, and general technology consulting work with user departments on enhancing and maintaining their information systems."
  ],
  "overview":[
    "Capital investment in technology enables the City to work more efficiently at a lower cost; to be more responsive to citizens; and to provide convenience for Boston&rsquo;s residents, businesses and visitors. Ongoing and new initiatives will build upon this progress, ensuring the City remains competitive and coordinated in computer information and communication technology."
  ],
  "fy_major_initiatives":[
    "In FY18, the Computer Aided Mass Appraisal (CAMA), an 18-year-old system, will begin to be replaced as part of a multi-year project.",
    "Expansion of the City&rsquo;s fiber optic network (BoNet), including connection to over 100 Boston Public School Buildings will continue in FY18.",
    "Begin a feasibility study to determine a cost effective and efficient way to expand and sustain the infrastructure that supports multiple City radio systems.",
    "In Enterprise Applications, DoIT will continue to assist the Fire Department in the development and implementation of a new time management system."
  ],
